  Bienvenue sur le site de Stellarium for Java (S4J), une version {{{http://java.sun.com}Java}} de {{{http://stellarium.org}Stellarium}}.

  S4J est un logiciel {{{http://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gpl}GPL}} gratuit which renders realistic skies in real time.
Avec Stellarium, vous voyez vraiment ce que vous pouvez voir avec vos yeux, des jumelles ou un petit télescope.
Stellarium est aussi utilisé par des {{{http://www.digitaliseducation.com}planetariums}}.

  S4J vise à fournir les mêmes fonctionnalités Stellarium d'origine mais sur la plate-forme Java,
permettant ainsi une plus grande portabilité à travers les plate-formes et les APIs bas-niveau (OpenGL, Direct3X),
une meilleur evolutivité, et un codage plus léger et facile.

  Jettez un oeil aux retours sur S4J :

   * {{{http://www.informit.com/blogs/blog.aspx?uk=JavaOne-Report}Frank Coyle on InformIT}} :
     vu une démo VRAIMENT cool - choisissez un endroit sur la terre et you get to see the stars
     that are above you in the sky - day and night, with annotations on the celestial objects.

   * {{{http://www.gtablue.com/technogeek/?p=8}on gtablue}} : JOGL / Stellarium (a cool planetarium-like program written in Java)

   * {{{http://technology.amis.nl/blog/?p=3153}Wouter van Reeven on AMIS}} : THE BEST AND COOLEST demo I have ever seen:
     The biggest hobby in my life is astronomy. It has been for a long time and I even have a degree in it.
     Seeing that the science wasn’t as much fun as the hobby, I persued a carreer in ICT. My colleague Lucas told me there was going to be a presentation
     about porting a planetarium program called Stellarium from C++ to Java using Java OpenGL, or JOGL.
     Getting a real good overview of what problems you get when trying to port an application from C++ to Java,
     the demos simply kicked ass! If you have some time, check out Stellarium for Java. It runs fast and smoothly,
     at least on modern computers. At one point Jerome Beau and Frederic Simon showed a star map
     and then opened up the Location selector map. While having pressed down the left mouse button
     and dragging the mouse pointer all over the Earth, the star map in the background got redrawn almost instantaneously.
     Another pretty cool feature was the fading in and out of constellation lines, azimuth and equatorial grid, etc etc.
     These guys really have done a tremendously good job with this application.
     After the presentation I gave them my cards and asked them to contact me.
     They are in need of astronomers and/or Java coders so if you like, go and help them.

